Expense Processing CLI Application

A Python-based CLI application that ingests expense data from CSV files, validates the data, stores it in a PostgreSQL database, and runs SQL-based analytics on the stored dataset.

The project demonstrates data ingestion pipelines, database interaction, Docker-based deployment, and automated testing using pytest.

----------------------------------------------------------------------
 Application Architecture Overview
----------------------------------------------------------------------
ExpenseProcessingCLIApp
│
├── app/
│   ├── main.py                 # CLI entry point
│   ├── ingestion.py            # CSV ingestion 
│   ├── multiple_csv_reader.py  # Reads multiple CSV files from folder(data)
│   ├── analytics_runner.py     # Executes SQL analytics queries(analytics/analytics.sql)
│   ├── db.py                   # Database connection 
│   ├── logger.py               # Centralized logging configuration
│
├── analytics/
│   └── analytics_queries.sql   # SQL queries for running analytics
│
├── data/
│   └── Sample1.csv    
│   └── Sample1.csv             # Folder with multiple CSVs
│
├── tests/
│   └── pytest test cases       # Pytest test cases
│
├── logs/
│   └── log1.log
│
├── .env
├── Dockerfile
├── docker-compose.yml
├── requirements.txt
├── .gitignore
├── pytest.ini
├── README

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Data Flow
----------------------------------------------------------------------
The application implements a data pipeline that processes raw CSV data into structured analytics results.

                CSV Files
                    │
                    ▼
                CSV Reader
        (multiple_csv_reader.py)
                    │
                    ▼
             Data Validation
            (expense_model.py)
                    │
                    ├── Valid rows → Insert into PostgreSQL
                    │
                    └── Invalid rows → Logged and skipped
                    │
                    ▼
         Insert into PostgreSQL Database
              (ingestion.py)
                    │
                    ▼
              SQL Analytics
            (analytics_runner.py)
                    │
                    ▼
          Query Results Printed to CLI
                    │
                    ▼
                 Pytest 

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Git workflow explanation
----------------------------------------------------------------------
Branch Structure
main
 ├── initial setup including CSV ingestion
 ├── feature/analytics
 └── feature/pytest-tests

Work Flow:

Initial commit

1. Initialize the project as git repo
cd ExpenseProcessingCLI
git .init

2. Stage all files in the project
 git add .   

3. Check all the files to be pushed to git are staged 
git status

4. Remove any files that are not to be commited to git
git restore --staged <file>
[to remove a file from staged list]
or
git rm --cached <file>
[If not wanted in future commits]

5. Commit the staged files with commit message
git commit -m "Initial Commit- Implement CSV ingestion module"

6. Create a empty repo in github and copy the repo url

7. Connect local Git repository to a remote repository 
git remote add origin <repo_url>

8. Mark the current branch as main
git branch -M main

9. Push the local main branch to the remote repository
git push -u origin main

To push a new branch: analytics/pytests

1. Create a feature branch
git checkout -b feature/analytics

2. Stage the changes and commit
git add .
git commit -m "Adding Analytics module"

3. Push branch
git push origin feature/analytics

4. Create Pull request on github

5. Merge the pull request

----------------------------------------------------------------------
Setup and run instructions (local + docker)
----------------------------------------------------------------------
1. Clone the repo
git clone <repo_url>

2. Add .env file in the project directory with required credentials:
POSTGRES_HOST=db # change it to localhost when running on local system
POSTGRES_DB=expenses
POSTGRES_USER= #userid
POSTGRES_PASSWORD= #userpassword
POSTGRES_PORT= #port

3. Install Dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

4. Run on Docker 
4.1 Build and start containers
    docker compose up --build -d
4.2 Run ingestion
    docker compose run python_app python -m app.main.py -ingest
4.3 Run analytics
    docker compose run python_app python -m app.main.py -analytics
4.4 Run unit tests
    docker compose run python_app python -m app.main.py -pytest
